  <section xml:id="SubSec-Homomorphisms">
    <title>Homomorphisms</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> and <m>S</m> be commutative rings with identity.
          A function <m>\p : R\to S</m> is a called
          <term>ring homomorphism</term>
          if it preserves addition, multiplication, and sends the identity of <m>R</m> to the identity of <m>S</m>.
          That is, for all <m>x,y\in R</m>:
          <ul>
          	<li><m>\p(x+y) = \p(x) + \p(y)</m>,</li>
          	<li><m>\p(xy) = \p(x)\p(y)</m>, and</li>
          	<li><m>\p(1_R) = 1_S</m>.</li>
          </ul>
          If <m>\p</m> is a bijection,
          we say that <m>\p</m> is an <term>isomorphism</term>
          and write <m>R\cong S</m>.
          If <m>\p : R\to R</m> is an isomorphism,
          we say <m>\p</m> is an <term>automorphism</term> of <m>R</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the function <m>\p : Z\to \Z_{5}</m> defined by <m>\p(x) = \overline{x}</m> is a homomorphism.
          Is it an isomorphism?
          Why or why not?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that <m>\p(x+y) = \overline{x+y} = \overline{x} + \overline{y} = \p(x) + \p(y)</m>,
          and similarly for multiplication.
          We observe that <m>\p</m> is not an isomorphism,
          as <m>\p(2) = \p(7) = \overline{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>

    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be commutative with identity and <m>I</m> an ideal of <m>R</m>.
          Define <m>\p: R\to R/I</m> by <m>\p(r) = r+I</m>.
          Then <m>\p</m> is a homomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <investigation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R = \Z_2[x]</m> and consider the map
          <m>F: R \to R</m> given by <m>F(p) = p^2</m>.
          Is <m>F</m> a homomorphism?
          An isomorphism?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </investigation>

    <exploration>
